Package org.opensextant.giscore.utils

Class DateTime

java.lang.Object
java.lang.Number
org.opensextant.giscore.utils.DateTime
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Cloneable, Comparable<DateTime>
public class DateTime extends Number implements Serializable, Cloneable, Comparable<DateTime>
The class DateTime represents a specific instant in time, with millisecond precision. DateTime has a date type for formatting matching associated XML Schema date types (e.g., gYear, gYearMonth, date, dateTime) which is used to format string representation as returned by the toString() method. 
 Examples:

 value                     type         format
 1997                      gYear        YYYY
 1997-07                   gYearMonth   YYYY-MM
 1997-07-16                date         YYYY-MM-DD
 1997-07-16T07:30:15Z      dateTime     YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ssZ
 1997-07-16T07:30:15.30Z   dateTime     YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.SSSZ

Class is thread-safe.

Extends Number such that it can safely be used in java.text.SimpleDateFormat.format().

Author:
Jason Mathews, MITRE Corp. created 4/17/14.

    • toString

      public String toString(DateTime.DateTimeType type)
      Creates a string representation of this DateTime object based on the type value.

      Here is list of types and corresponding formats: 

         date -> yyyy-MM-dd
   gYearMonth -> yyyy-MM
   gYear -> yyyy
   dateTime -> yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss.SSS'Z' (default)
      If want custom format use java.text.SimpleDateFormat.format().
      Parameters:
      type - DateTimeType used to select format for this DateTime object
      Returns:
      a string representation of this date

    • toUTCString

      public String toUTCString()
      Creates a string representation of this DateTime object of the form: 
       YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.SSSZ
      where:
      • yyyy is the year, as four decimal digits.
      • MM is the month, as two decimal digits.
      • DD is the day of the month (01 through 31), as two decimal digits.
      • hh is the hour of the day (00 through 23), as two decimal digits.
      • mm is the minute within the hour (00 through 59), as two decimal digits.
      • ss is the second within the minute (00 through 60), as two decimal digits.
      Returns:
      a string representation of this date, using the XML Schema dateTime convention with UTC time zone.
